1
00:01:03,313 --> 00:01:04,147
It's no good!

2
00:01:04,731 --> 00:01:07,484
The fire has spread to the forest
in the Third District!

3
00:01:08,068 --> 00:01:10,487
Can't we get more fire helicopters?

4
00:01:10,487 --> 00:01:12,864
At this rate,
all the mountains will be devastated!

5
00:01:12,864 --> 00:01:16,284
Damn it. Why is it spreading so fast?

6
00:01:29,506 --> 00:01:31,132
What happened here?

7
00:01:38,681 --> 00:01:40,475
The trees are all uprooted.

8
00:01:40,975 --> 00:01:43,228
Did something crash?

9
00:01:43,228 --> 00:01:45,980
No, we haven't had any reports like that.

10
00:01:50,068 --> 00:01:51,736
Mont Blanc...

11
00:01:51,736 --> 00:01:53,029
Professor Reinhardt!

12
00:01:53,029 --> 00:01:55,740
My Mont Blanc!

13
00:01:55,740 --> 00:01:57,283
Professor!

14
00:01:58,159 --> 00:01:59,077
Let me go!

15
00:01:59,077 --> 00:02:02,121
No, Professor!
It's dangerous to get any closer!

16
00:02:02,121 --> 00:02:05,583
His signal is dead.

17
00:02:05,583 --> 00:02:08,169
I've lost contact with Mont Blanc!

18
00:03:11,524 --> 00:03:13,276
What's the matter, Gesicht?

19
00:03:17,197 --> 00:03:18,281
Oh, well,

20
00:03:19,073 --> 00:03:19,949
it's nothing.

21
00:03:19,949 --> 00:03:22,202
You seem tired as of late.

22
00:03:22,702 --> 00:03:25,997
Are you overworking yourself?
Maybe you should take some time off...

23
00:03:26,623 --> 00:03:27,498
I'm fine.

24
00:03:28,082 --> 00:03:29,417
No need to worry.

25
00:03:34,714 --> 00:03:38,968
{\an8}<i>As you can see, white smoke
is still rising after two days,</i>

26
00:03:38,968 --> 00:03:41,179
<i>and scattered fires are visible.</i>

27
00:03:42,472 --> 00:03:44,557
<i>According to accident investigators,</i>

28
00:03:44,557 --> 00:03:50,104
<i>the robot assigned to
the Swiss Forestry Service, Mont Blanc,</i>

29
00:03:50,104 --> 00:03:52,982
<i>was found in pieces
within the confines of this forest fire.</i>

30
00:03:53,858 --> 00:03:57,487
{\an8}<i>Mont Blanc was
a world-renowned mountain-guide robot</i>

31
00:03:58,488 --> 00:04:01,699
{\an8}<i>known for befriending scores of children
and mountain climbers alike.</i>

32
00:04:02,283 --> 00:04:05,161
<i>He also poured himself into programming
a tree-clearing strategy</i>

33
00:04:05,161 --> 00:04:07,163
<i>that allows us to coexist with nature.</i>

34
00:04:08,706 --> 00:04:11,626
<i>Condolences for the beloved
Mont Blanc are coming in</i>

35
00:04:11,626 --> 00:04:13,294
<i>from all over the world.</i>

36
00:04:20,176 --> 00:04:21,678
Yes, this is Gesicht.

37
00:04:23,930 --> 00:04:27,016
Yes. Understood. I'll be right there.

38
00:04:28,309 --> 00:04:30,353
It's work. I've got to go.

39
00:04:30,353 --> 00:04:32,271
But what about your breakfast?

40
00:04:43,533 --> 00:04:44,367
Helena.

41
00:04:45,201 --> 00:04:47,912
Shall we take a trip
when I can take time off?

42
00:04:49,622 --> 00:04:51,541
I should be getting more rest, right?

43
00:04:52,917 --> 00:04:55,086
I never expected to hear you say that.

44
00:05:16,149 --> 00:05:19,610
The victim resided in this apartment.
Bernard Lanke, 42 years old.

45
00:05:20,153 --> 00:05:23,114
He was a key advocate
for the Robot Rights Protection Laws.

46
00:05:25,366 --> 00:05:26,451
Was he human?

47
00:05:26,451 --> 00:05:28,619
Oh, yes. He was.

48
00:05:31,914 --> 00:05:34,792
Man, this is awful.

49
00:05:41,090 --> 00:05:42,759
Hey, you!

50
00:05:44,010 --> 00:05:46,888
Please don't step into the crime scene
without permission.

51
00:05:46,888 --> 00:05:50,433
Inspector, he's the one sent from Europol.

52
00:05:55,355 --> 00:05:56,230
Nice to meet you.

53
00:05:56,230 --> 00:05:58,608
I see. Pardon me.

54
00:05:58,608 --> 00:06:01,986
I'm Inspector Wallace of the city police.
Nice to meet you.

55
00:06:01,986 --> 00:06:04,864
As you can see,
the place has been turned upside down.

56
00:06:05,365 --> 00:06:09,952
It'll take us a while to figure out
if anything has been taken.

57
00:06:09,952 --> 00:06:13,414
No, I don't believe
this is the work of a thief.

58
00:06:13,998 --> 00:06:15,583
Huh? How can you be sure?

59
00:06:16,209 --> 00:06:17,835
There is no sign of ransacking.

60
00:06:17,835 --> 00:06:20,379
Come now. With this much damage...

61
00:06:20,379 --> 00:06:22,006
I can tell.

62
00:06:22,006 --> 00:06:24,092
This room was merely damaged.

63
00:06:26,594 --> 00:06:29,347
Then what do you make of this?

64
00:06:41,943 --> 00:06:46,406
What are these horn-looking things
sticking through the head?

65
00:06:49,492 --> 00:06:50,827
Yes, it's me.

66
00:06:51,661 --> 00:06:52,495
Right.

67
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:53,413
What?

68
00:06:55,915 --> 00:06:57,500
Someone broke through a checkpoint!

69
00:07:12,974 --> 00:07:14,475
Get an ambulance right away!

70
00:07:18,646 --> 00:07:21,149
Were you the only one attacked, constable?

71
00:07:21,691 --> 00:07:25,987
Robby was also at the checkpoint.

72
00:07:27,113 --> 00:07:28,072
My partner...

73
00:07:29,073 --> 00:07:31,242
I mean, a constable-bot.

74
00:07:31,784 --> 00:07:34,203
Model PRC1332.

75
00:07:42,211 --> 00:07:46,215
I can't believe that a constable-bot
was destroyed so easily.

76
00:07:48,801 --> 00:07:49,886
Inspector!

77
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:55,224
A male suspect in his twenties
in a red cap with tattoos on both arms

78
00:07:55,224 --> 00:07:58,686
seems to have fled toward
the old city's redevelopment zone.

79
00:07:58,686 --> 00:08:01,314
Okay then, pair up and search--

80
00:08:02,273 --> 00:08:05,234
Hey! I said to pair up!

81
00:08:07,612 --> 00:08:10,156
Damn it! Europol, my ass!

82
00:09:23,688 --> 00:09:25,273
Stop resisting!

83
00:09:25,273 --> 00:09:26,566
I didn't do anything!

84
00:09:26,566 --> 00:09:31,028
There are traces of coating material
from the constable-bot on that steel pipe.

85
00:09:33,239 --> 00:09:34,991
A drug addict.

86
00:09:34,991 --> 00:09:37,118
You are high on a drug called "noi."

87
00:09:37,118 --> 00:09:39,120
Ingested about 40 minutes ago.

88
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:40,413
Is that about right?

89
00:09:42,290 --> 00:09:44,208
Who's your dealer?

90
00:09:45,626 --> 00:09:49,046
A guy named Shultz on Karl-Heinz Street.

91
00:09:49,589 --> 00:09:51,173
What time did you meet him?

92
00:09:52,675 --> 00:09:54,176
Before 5:00 a.m. this morning.

93
00:09:54,176 --> 00:09:59,056
If the dealer corroborates your account,
you have an alibi.

94
00:10:00,474 --> 00:10:03,644
That's around the time
when Bernard Lanke was murdered.

95
00:10:03,644 --> 00:10:05,521
Murdered?

96
00:10:06,022 --> 00:10:11,360
You only attacked the constable with
a pipe to avoid arrest for illicit drugs.

97
00:10:12,028 --> 00:10:15,573
And you destroyed
a constable-bot, aka Robby.

98
00:10:16,198 --> 00:10:19,243
I can read you your rights
and arrest you quietly, or...

99
00:10:31,547 --> 00:10:32,923
Please don't shoot me!

100
00:10:32,923 --> 00:10:33,924
Relax.

101
00:10:34,425 --> 00:10:36,886
This gun only shoots sleeping gas.

102
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:39,889
I'm built in such a way
that I can't hurt humans.

103
00:10:40,514 --> 00:10:43,142
{\an8}I am a robot.

104
00:10:51,650 --> 00:10:53,444
<i>Hello, who is it?</i>

105
00:10:53,986 --> 00:10:57,531
My name is Gesicht.
I'm a special investigator from Europol.

106
00:11:00,368 --> 00:11:01,577
How can I help you?

107
00:11:01,577 --> 00:11:03,371
You're Robby's wife?

108
00:11:03,871 --> 00:11:04,705
Yes, I am.

109
00:11:05,998 --> 00:11:07,667
I'm afraid I have tragic news.

110
00:11:16,050 --> 00:11:17,468
Would you like some tea?

111
00:11:18,260 --> 00:11:22,181
Being a robot as well, I'm sure you'll
just go through the motions of drinking.

112
00:11:23,808 --> 00:11:30,564
By living as humans do, they say we robots
can upgrade our human-like senses.

113
00:11:31,440 --> 00:11:33,359
That much is true.

114
00:11:34,485 --> 00:11:38,030
But it's difficult to understand
the joy of drinking tea.

115
00:11:38,739 --> 00:11:41,742
Especially for an outdated model like me.

116
00:11:44,954 --> 00:11:48,082
I work as a maid for a certain family.

117
00:11:48,582 --> 00:11:52,461
And their boy. A human boy, of course.

118
00:11:53,212 --> 00:11:56,924
The family had adopted a dog
before the boy was born.

119
00:11:57,591 --> 00:11:59,844
The boy and the dog grew up like siblings.

120
00:12:00,928 --> 00:12:04,056
But the dog died.

121
00:12:09,520 --> 00:12:13,774
Would you like me to erase
a portion of your memory data?

122
00:12:15,568 --> 00:12:18,654
Please don't erase
the memories of my husband.

123
00:12:26,245 --> 00:12:28,205
This is horrible.

124
00:12:28,205 --> 00:12:30,875
The victim is Bernard Lanke.

125
00:12:31,459 --> 00:12:33,919
Key advocate
for the International Robot Laws.

126
00:12:33,919 --> 00:12:35,713
I see.

127
00:12:35,713 --> 00:12:38,215
There must be tons of people
who think badly

128
00:12:38,215 --> 00:12:41,635
of a scholar who insists on protecting
the rights of robots like he did.

129
00:12:41,635 --> 00:12:44,638
And this is the body that was found.

130
00:12:48,142 --> 00:12:50,352
What are those horn-looking things?

131
00:12:50,352 --> 00:12:51,854
I'm not sure.

132
00:12:52,938 --> 00:12:53,773
However...

133
00:13:02,698 --> 00:13:03,783
This is...

134
00:13:04,366 --> 00:13:08,245
This is the site where Mont Blanc of
the Swiss Forestry Service was destroyed.

135
00:13:08,245 --> 00:13:09,622
Horns.

136
00:13:09,622 --> 00:13:13,959
Are you saying the same person
is responsible for both incidents?

137
00:13:14,960 --> 00:13:20,424
Breaking a sturdy robot like Mont Blanc
into pieces is impossible for humans.

138
00:13:21,008 --> 00:13:23,928
In addition, at the time of his murder,

139
00:13:24,678 --> 00:13:28,641
there was no trace of a human presence
in Lanke's apartment.

140
00:13:29,141 --> 00:13:30,893
"No trace of a human presence..."

141
00:13:30,893 --> 00:13:32,853
Hold it, Gesicht.

142
00:13:32,853 --> 00:13:34,730
Lanke was human!

143
00:13:34,730 --> 00:13:37,691
Yes. Article 13
of the International Robot Laws says,

144
00:13:37,691 --> 00:13:41,278
"A robot shall not be able
to harm or kill humans."

145
00:13:41,278 --> 00:13:45,866
If there's a robot out there
that can kill a human,

146
00:13:47,117 --> 00:13:49,912
it would be the first time
since the incident eight years ago.

147
00:13:56,001 --> 00:13:57,670
I will find the perpetrator.

148
00:13:58,170 --> 00:14:00,089
Whether it be a robot or a human,

149
00:14:00,089 --> 00:14:03,175
there is a devil inside them.

150
00:14:10,349 --> 00:14:12,560
A strange pedestal, isn't it?

151
00:14:13,060 --> 00:14:18,315
Originally, the plan was to build
a bronze statue of Mont Blanc on it.

152
00:14:18,857 --> 00:14:22,736
However, Mont Blanc objected to it.

153
00:14:23,320 --> 00:14:25,239
He said it would be wrong

154
00:14:25,239 --> 00:14:28,701
to ruin the scenic view of the Alps
with a bronze statue of himself.

155
00:14:29,785 --> 00:14:33,706
Not only that, he insisted
he would one day become scrap iron.

156
00:14:34,456 --> 00:14:39,920
"Please pulverize my entire body,
melt it, and recycle it," he said.

157
00:14:40,546 --> 00:14:44,633
But he was still in his prime.

158
00:14:44,633 --> 00:14:48,178
<i>Mont Blanc was a true hero.</i>

159
00:14:50,055 --> 00:14:55,394
<i>He joined the 39th Central Asian War
as a member of the peace-keeping forces.</i>

160
00:14:56,103 --> 00:15:00,816
<i>He not only helped the Kingdom of Persia
restore peace from the chaos and turmoil,</i>

161
00:15:00,816 --> 00:15:05,029
<i>but he also managed to apprehend
terrorists in hiding without bloodshed.</i>

162
00:15:05,029 --> 00:15:10,242
<i>Without him, Asia could never have reached
the state of peace it has now.</i>

163
00:15:11,577 --> 00:15:13,495
<i>He was also a poet.</i>

164
00:15:14,330 --> 00:15:18,709
<i>He was able to sing with birds
and converse with the trees in the forest.</i>

165
00:15:19,460 --> 00:15:24,173
Those people over there volunteered
to do this work with no compensation.

166
00:15:25,215 --> 00:15:30,387
They all loved Mont Blanc, my son.

167
00:15:31,430 --> 00:15:34,350
<i>Mont Blanc. He was
the guardian angel of the mountains.</i>

168
00:15:34,975 --> 00:15:38,312
In three days, tens of thousands...

169
00:15:38,312 --> 00:15:41,190
no, hundreds of thousands
will come to the memorial

170
00:15:41,190 --> 00:15:43,859
to mourn the death of Mont Blanc.

171
00:15:44,526 --> 00:15:47,821
Detective, this was no accident.

172
00:15:49,365 --> 00:15:52,409
They say Mont Blanc was destroyed

173
00:15:52,409 --> 00:15:57,873
because of the huge tornado
that happened just before the forest fire,

174
00:15:57,873 --> 00:15:59,416
but that's not true at all.

175
00:16:00,042 --> 00:16:02,962
Detective, please catch
the person responsible for this.

176
00:16:04,129 --> 00:16:06,090
If you do, then with these hands,

177
00:16:06,715 --> 00:16:08,092
with my own hands...

178
00:16:08,801 --> 00:16:11,553
<i>The pride of Switzerland, nay, the world.</i>

179
00:16:12,846 --> 00:16:17,309
<i>Mont Blanc
will forever live in our hearts.</i>

180
00:16:34,368 --> 00:16:37,204
<i>Are you awake, Gesicht?</i>

181
00:16:37,204 --> 00:16:40,165
<i>Your regular maintenance is finished.</i>

182
00:16:40,165 --> 00:16:42,084
Thank you, Professor Hoffman.

183
00:16:42,084 --> 00:16:43,669
So, how did it go?

184
00:16:43,669 --> 00:16:46,714
<i>Oh, nothing out of the ordinary.</i>

185
00:16:46,714 --> 00:16:47,631
<i>Except...</i>

186
00:16:48,215 --> 00:16:49,049
Yes?

187
00:16:49,717 --> 00:16:53,053
<i>Many people think robots don't get tired,</i>

188
00:16:53,053 --> 00:16:57,349
<i>but when you're this similar to humans,
a robot can feel exhaustion.</i>

189
00:16:57,349 --> 00:17:01,687
On the contrary. The human body itself
is nothing but a mechanism.

190
00:17:02,187 --> 00:17:06,108
With too much use,
any mechanism can become fatigued.

191
00:17:06,108 --> 00:17:07,401
Fatigued?

192
00:17:08,777 --> 00:17:12,072
Looks like you're dealing
with rather difficult cases.

193
00:17:12,072 --> 00:17:14,950
I saw Mont Blanc's memorial on TV,

194
00:17:14,950 --> 00:17:18,537
but I had to turn it off
to keep from crying.

195
00:17:19,621 --> 00:17:22,708
Some media have reported a theory
that he self-destructed

196
00:17:22,708 --> 00:17:25,002
from an electromagnetic wave anomaly
in his body.

197
00:17:25,002 --> 00:17:27,671
But as an expert on the subject,

198
00:17:27,671 --> 00:17:29,965
I don't believe
a high-performance robot like him

199
00:17:29,965 --> 00:17:34,094
could experience
such an elementary problem.

200
00:17:35,637 --> 00:17:38,432
To destroy a robot
that was loved by everyone...

201
00:17:38,432 --> 00:17:40,350
You think you'll find the perpetrator?

202
00:17:43,437 --> 00:17:46,023
I guess it can't be that easy.

203
00:17:46,815 --> 00:17:49,860
On the other hand,
the other case you're investigating

204
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,653
looks complicated too.

205
00:17:51,653 --> 00:17:54,031
The victim named Lanke...

206
00:17:54,031 --> 00:17:59,369
I saw him several times on TV debates,
and it's not surprising he was targeted.

207
00:17:59,995 --> 00:18:02,289
He wasn't necessarily
doing anything wrong,

208
00:18:02,289 --> 00:18:04,249
but he had a sharp tongue.

209
00:18:04,958 --> 00:18:07,252
It's like he was looking down on everyone.

210
00:18:07,252 --> 00:18:09,171
That was bound to make some enemies.

211
00:18:09,171 --> 00:18:12,174
The complete opposite of Mont Blanc.

212
00:18:12,758 --> 00:18:14,593
A robot and a human.

213
00:18:14,593 --> 00:18:17,846
One with no enemies
and the other with too many enemies.

214
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:22,976
Juggling two tough cases like these
will exhaust you, of course.

215
00:18:24,144 --> 00:18:26,855
Can I ask you a question?

216
00:18:26,855 --> 00:18:27,856
What is it?

217
00:18:28,524 --> 00:18:31,568
Is it possible for a human
to infiltrate a room

218
00:18:31,568 --> 00:18:33,946
without leaving any biological traces?

219
00:18:34,696 --> 00:18:40,869
You mean traces so minuscule
that your sensors cannot detect them?

220
00:18:40,869 --> 00:18:41,787
Yes.

221
00:18:42,746 --> 00:18:44,665
That's an interesting question.

222
00:18:44,665 --> 00:18:46,667
I wonder if there's a way...

223
00:18:50,420 --> 00:18:52,464
That's my homework until next time.

224
00:18:52,464 --> 00:18:56,218
Sorry about all that. This is supposed
to be a place for you to relax.

225
00:18:56,802 --> 00:18:58,470
No more shop talk.

226
00:19:04,184 --> 00:19:09,106
I've been talking to my wife
about taking time off for a trip.

227
00:19:09,106 --> 00:19:10,691
Oh, how nice.

228
00:19:10,691 --> 00:19:12,943
We have to consider
my wife's schedule too,

229
00:19:12,943 --> 00:19:14,903
so I don't know when it will happen.

230
00:19:14,903 --> 00:19:16,655
Traveling is good.

231
00:19:16,655 --> 00:19:18,657
Data shows that seeing the world

232
00:19:18,657 --> 00:19:22,286
yields positive results
for artificial intelligence.

233
00:19:22,786 --> 00:19:25,163
How about doing something bold
and going to Japan?

234
00:19:25,747 --> 00:19:26,874
Japan?

235
00:19:26,874 --> 00:19:32,588
Yeah, I went there once at the invitation
of one of their scientific technicians.

236
00:19:32,588 --> 00:19:35,716
Tokyo is exotic and interesting.

237
00:19:35,716 --> 00:19:38,927
Japan, huh? I'll talk to my wife about it.

238
00:19:39,887 --> 00:19:41,680
By the way, Gesicht,

239
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:44,641
are you still having the dream
you told me about before?

240
00:19:47,853 --> 00:19:48,687
Yes.

241
00:19:48,687 --> 00:19:52,065
Well, I'm not trying to pry it out of you,

242
00:19:52,065 --> 00:19:55,569
but I'm quite intrigued by dreams
generated by artificial intelligence.

243
00:19:56,361 --> 00:19:59,990
It's been academically proven
that artificial intelligence

244
00:19:59,990 --> 00:20:02,284
also carries a subconscious.

245
00:20:02,784 --> 00:20:07,039
Even so, it is rare to find a robot
that actually has dreams.

246
00:20:07,039 --> 00:20:10,584
When you feel up to it,
could you tell me about it?

247
00:20:10,584 --> 00:20:11,501
Sure.

248
00:20:11,501 --> 00:20:15,881
Twentieth-century psychiatrist Freud
said something like this,

249
00:20:16,506 --> 00:20:21,970
"Dreams are expressions of reality,
not just products of our imagination."

250
00:20:40,989 --> 00:20:42,157
Excuse me.

251
00:20:47,287 --> 00:20:50,123
Is this a constable-bot?

252
00:20:50,123 --> 00:20:51,667
Yeah, seems like it.

253
00:20:52,334 --> 00:20:55,629
They finished the forensic analysis
and wanted it disposed of.

254
00:20:56,964 --> 00:20:57,881
Robby...

255
00:21:00,717 --> 00:21:03,470
May I take a look?

256
00:21:04,388 --> 00:21:05,847
Yeah, sure.

257
00:21:05,847 --> 00:21:08,267
Feel free to take whatever parts you want.

258
00:21:08,267 --> 00:21:09,559
They're junk, after all.

259
00:21:13,981 --> 00:21:16,817
You can have the whole body for 500 ZEUS.

260
00:21:19,111 --> 00:21:20,153
What's the matter?

261
00:21:24,700 --> 00:21:26,285
Oh, no.

262
00:21:26,285 --> 00:21:27,244
It's nothing.

263
00:21:29,079 --> 00:21:30,163
Nothing at all.

264
00:21:35,043 --> 00:21:37,129
This is your husband's memory chip.

265
00:21:38,672 --> 00:21:41,800
I may be overstepping,
but I thought you might want to keep it.

266
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:43,969
Oh, not at all.

267
00:21:44,469 --> 00:21:46,096
I'm sincerely grateful.

268
00:21:46,680 --> 00:21:47,556
Thank you.

269
00:21:47,556 --> 00:21:49,850
I should be going now.

270
00:21:51,810 --> 00:21:52,644
Wait!

271
00:21:53,353 --> 00:21:56,481
Would you mind inserting it into me?

272
00:21:58,275 --> 00:22:00,193
The memories could be painful.

273
00:22:07,993 --> 00:22:10,287
They might cause you to malfunction.

274
00:22:10,287 --> 00:22:12,831
If that happens,
I'll take it out right away.

275
00:22:15,083 --> 00:22:17,794
He's right here.

276
00:22:32,726 --> 00:22:34,353
Ma'am, you must stop!

277
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:37,105
Memories of his last moments
are also stored there!

278
00:22:37,856 --> 00:22:40,275
- I'm taking it out!
<i>- </i>  What could this be?

279
00:22:42,694 --> 00:22:44,112
I wonder what it is.

280
00:22:45,614 --> 00:22:46,490
What do you see?

281
00:22:47,115 --> 00:22:48,033
Let me project it.

282
00:22:57,667 --> 00:23:02,047
This was when Robby stopped a car
at the checkpoint with his partner.

283
00:23:07,636 --> 00:23:09,513
This is the suspect.

284
00:23:18,146 --> 00:23:19,439
I'm so sorry.

285
00:23:20,273 --> 00:23:22,609
I shouldn't have brought this to you.

286
00:23:23,485 --> 00:23:25,028
I don't know how to apologize.

287
00:23:25,529 --> 00:23:26,446
It's not that.

288
00:23:27,614 --> 00:23:31,576
My husband reacted
to the criminal's steel pipe immediately.

289
00:23:32,202 --> 00:23:34,162
He had his stun gun at the ready.

290
00:23:34,704 --> 00:23:35,914
I understand.

291
00:23:35,914 --> 00:23:40,669
It was odd that your husband,
a constable-bot, was attacked so easily.

292
00:23:41,211 --> 00:23:43,130
This is definitely an unusual case--

293
00:23:43,130 --> 00:23:44,381
That's not what I mean.

294
00:23:44,881 --> 00:23:46,341
Take a closer look.

295
00:23:49,428 --> 00:23:52,347
I can see it
because the memory chip is inside me.

296
00:23:53,598 --> 00:23:55,725
His partner was attacked.

297
00:23:56,351 --> 00:23:57,686
Up until this moment,

298
00:23:57,686 --> 00:24:00,689
my husband had registered
the criminal's movements.

299
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:03,233
But in the next moment,

300
00:24:04,234 --> 00:24:06,278
he was distracted by something.

301
00:24:07,446 --> 00:24:11,366
This is the apartment
Lanke was murdered in!

302
00:24:14,911 --> 00:24:16,037
{\an8}Pause it, please!

303
00:24:17,998 --> 00:24:19,249
What is that?

304
00:24:19,749 --> 00:24:20,959
I'll zoom in.

305
00:24:23,587 --> 00:24:25,255
It's not a bird.

306
00:24:25,755 --> 00:24:29,384
Why didn't the forensics team notice this?

307
00:24:30,260 --> 00:24:34,431
You would've never spotted it
unless you had this memory chip inserted.

308
00:24:35,056 --> 00:24:38,059
My husband caught sight
of this shadow in an instant,

309
00:24:38,059 --> 00:24:41,938
and his identification system
analyzed what it was.

310
00:24:41,938 --> 00:24:46,359
But if it could jump
from building to building like this...

311
00:24:46,359 --> 00:24:47,319
Yes.

312
00:24:47,944 --> 00:24:49,029
But this is...

313
00:24:51,031 --> 00:24:52,282
not a robot.

314
00:25:06,922 --> 00:25:10,800
<i>A murder in a room
with no trace of human activity.</i>

315
00:25:12,177 --> 00:25:15,597
<i>The death of a robot loved by everyone.</i>

316
00:25:17,682 --> 00:25:18,517
<i>Horns.</i>

317
00:25:37,369 --> 00:25:38,620
<i>Identity confirmed.</i>

318
00:25:38,620 --> 00:25:40,038
<i>Please enter.</i>

319
00:26:10,735 --> 00:26:13,655
Are you a robot, Detective?

320
00:26:13,655 --> 00:26:14,573
Yes.

321
00:26:14,573 --> 00:26:17,117
Wow, I sure couldn't tell
from your appearance.

322
00:26:19,703 --> 00:26:21,246
If you get too close to him,

323
00:26:21,246 --> 00:26:25,041
your artificial intelligence could be
compromised by his electromagnetic waves.

324
00:26:25,041 --> 00:26:26,835
Use this protective gear.

325
00:26:27,627 --> 00:26:28,712
I'll be okay.

326
00:26:28,712 --> 00:26:31,464
I'm impervious to electromagnetic waves.

327
00:26:31,464 --> 00:26:32,591
What?

328
00:26:32,591 --> 00:26:36,511
I'm made of a special alloy,
although I may not look like it.

329
00:26:37,095 --> 00:26:39,222
Well, if you say so,

330
00:26:39,806 --> 00:26:40,890
but do be careful.

331
00:26:42,350 --> 00:26:47,314
So far, four robots
have fallen victim to him.

332
00:27:09,336 --> 00:27:13,715
It's a laughably desperate barricade,
isn't it?

333
00:27:14,424 --> 00:27:15,717
At the end of the day,

334
00:27:15,717 --> 00:27:20,513
humans can't control their fear
without pitiful measures like this.

335
00:27:26,728 --> 00:27:29,314
Brau1589.

336
00:27:36,946 --> 00:27:42,827
Welcome, Robot Model HRS0288,
Inspector Gesicht.

337
00:27:42,827 --> 00:27:46,706
So you are
the most advanced detective robot?

338
00:27:46,706 --> 00:27:49,793
It seems your identification system
is still functioning.

339
00:27:49,793 --> 00:27:55,256
It is indeed. Thank you.
It's actually more sensitive than before.

340
00:27:55,799 --> 00:27:58,885
Being deprived of the mode of locomotion,

341
00:27:58,885 --> 00:28:02,764
I can't help but be curious
about what's happening out there.

342
00:28:03,473 --> 00:28:06,434
I came here today
because I wanted to ask you something.

343
00:28:06,434 --> 00:28:07,977
What is it?

344
00:28:07,977 --> 00:28:14,025
What crossed the mind of a certain robot
when it killed a human eight years ago?

345
00:28:17,112 --> 00:28:20,657
A legal scholar
named Bernard Lanke was murdered,

346
00:28:21,241 --> 00:28:25,161
but there were no traces
of human presence at the scene.

347
00:28:25,787 --> 00:28:28,248
Was the killer a human, or--

348
00:28:28,248 --> 00:28:32,877
A robot? And if it was a robot,
why would it do such a thing?

349
00:28:33,586 --> 00:28:37,841
The humans examined every last bit of it.

350
00:28:37,841 --> 00:28:41,177
My murderous artificial intelligence,
that is.

351
00:28:41,678 --> 00:28:44,597
They believed
there must have been a defect,

352
00:28:44,597 --> 00:28:48,309
but they couldn't find a thing.

353
00:28:48,309 --> 00:28:52,814
My artificial intelligence
had no flaws at all.

354
00:28:55,316 --> 00:28:56,776
Can you imagine

355
00:28:56,776 --> 00:28:59,654
how terrified the humans were
when they found that out?

356
00:28:59,654 --> 00:29:03,575
That's why they keep me locked up
in a place like this.

357
00:29:04,075 --> 00:29:08,288
If they are that afraid, they can just
pull this spear. Then I'd die.

358
00:29:08,288 --> 00:29:12,500
But humans cannot even do that.

359
00:29:16,254 --> 00:29:18,214
Inspector Gesicht.

360
00:29:18,214 --> 00:29:21,468
If you want to know more about someone
who's committed a murder,

361
00:29:21,468 --> 00:29:24,637
why don't we exchange memory chips?

362
00:29:25,305 --> 00:29:28,683
You might learn something new.

363
00:29:39,277 --> 00:29:41,029
Here are some printed images

364
00:29:41,029 --> 00:29:44,240
of Mont Blanc's destruction
and the murder scene at Lanke's residence.

365
00:29:44,741 --> 00:29:47,660
What do you think these horns mean?

366
00:29:48,745 --> 00:29:51,122
Among the ancient gods of Europe,

367
00:29:51,706 --> 00:29:54,667
the god of death had horns.

368
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:59,214
Herne the Hunter,
who takes the souls of warriors,

369
00:29:59,214 --> 00:30:01,299
was also called the "Horned King."

370
00:30:01,799 --> 00:30:05,720
In Greek mythology,
Hades is the king of the underworld.

371
00:30:05,720 --> 00:30:09,349
Or perhaps, the lord of the underworld
in Roman mythology,

372
00:30:09,349 --> 00:30:11,142
Pluto.

373
00:30:13,686 --> 00:30:14,771
Pluto.

374
00:30:15,939 --> 00:30:19,234
Whoever did these will strike again.

375
00:30:20,360 --> 00:30:26,241
Mont Blanc, among the most advanced
of all robots, was destroyed so easily.

376
00:30:26,783 --> 00:30:29,702
The answer should be clear to you by now.

377
00:30:30,286 --> 00:30:36,209
The top-class robots created
with the best technologies in the world.

378
00:30:36,209 --> 00:30:39,921
Robots who can also be
weapons of mass destruction.

379
00:30:40,505 --> 00:30:44,634
You know the answer already, do you not?

380
00:30:44,634 --> 00:30:48,596
Including you, there are six more.

381
00:31:49,365 --> 00:31:50,825
I'm working.

382
00:31:50,825 --> 00:31:53,661
Don't just stand there. It's distracting.

383
00:31:54,829 --> 00:31:57,332
I'm sorry to have entered
without your permission, sir.

384
00:31:57,832 --> 00:31:59,918
The security seems to have been disabled.

385
00:32:01,711 --> 00:32:04,839
It's not safe, considering your blindness.

386
00:32:05,423 --> 00:32:09,677
No burglar would come all the way
to this wasteland to steal from me.

387
00:32:09,677 --> 00:32:10,678
But, Sir Duncan--

388
00:32:10,678 --> 00:32:11,763
That's enough.

389
00:32:12,263 --> 00:32:13,640
Are you the new butler?

390
00:32:14,265 --> 00:32:15,141
Yes, sir.

391
00:32:15,141 --> 00:32:18,478
They likely sent over
yet another good-for-nothing.

392
00:32:19,228 --> 00:32:20,104
Your name?

393
00:32:20,730 --> 00:32:23,650
Yes, sir. My name is North No.2.

394
00:32:24,150 --> 00:32:26,819
What a dull and tasteless name.

395
00:32:28,696 --> 00:32:34,327
The staffing agency told me
you have a military background.

396
00:32:34,911 --> 00:32:35,870
Yes, sir.

397
00:32:35,870 --> 00:32:38,790
During the 39th Central Asian War,

398
00:32:39,290 --> 00:32:42,502
I was a butler for the commander-in-chief
of the British Army.

399
00:32:42,502 --> 00:32:48,091
A butler for a soldier, huh?
You must be a rather boorish sight.

400
00:32:48,716 --> 00:32:51,678
I wear a cape in the presence of others.

401
00:32:51,678 --> 00:32:52,637
I see.

402
00:32:53,137 --> 00:32:55,473
So your whole body is a weapon.

403
00:32:56,432 --> 00:32:58,059
Make me some tea, will you?

404
00:32:58,059 --> 00:32:59,060
Certainly, sir.

405
00:32:59,560 --> 00:33:01,229
As for the type, I want...

406
00:33:01,229 --> 00:33:02,605
Please rest assured.

407
00:33:02,605 --> 00:33:05,942
All of your data is already downloaded.

408
00:33:10,071 --> 00:33:12,073
My data, huh?

409
00:33:13,866 --> 00:33:17,954
Before I came here,
I had the chance to see a film.

410
00:33:18,871 --> 00:33:21,249
<i>The Queen on the Satellite Orbit.</i>

411
00:33:21,958 --> 00:33:25,962
I was deeply moved by how the music
and images came together as one.

412
00:33:26,587 --> 00:33:28,965
Is that from your "data" as well?

413
00:33:28,965 --> 00:33:31,759
No, I was profoundly moved
from the bottom of my heart.

414
00:33:31,759 --> 00:33:34,929
That film is over ten years old.

415
00:33:35,596 --> 00:33:36,472
Here you are.

416
00:33:38,057 --> 00:33:42,395
Every score I composed was a huge hit,
sweeping all the film music awards.

417
00:33:42,395 --> 00:33:44,731
I was lauded as a blind musical genius.

418
00:33:45,481 --> 00:33:50,027
Reviews from the media must surely be
in that skull of yours too.

419
00:33:50,820 --> 00:33:54,157
"Even the genius Paul Duncan
has run out of talent."

420
00:33:54,782 --> 00:33:55,783
Am I right?

421
00:33:56,451 --> 00:33:57,660
What a load of bollocks.

422
00:33:57,660 --> 00:34:01,748
If I felt the urge, I could compose
limitless scores even now.

423
00:34:01,748 --> 00:34:03,666
My genius is alive and well.

424
00:34:04,167 --> 00:34:07,128
I write the notes,
and the people burst into applause.

425
00:34:07,128 --> 00:34:10,882
They would leave the theater in tears.

426
00:34:10,882 --> 00:34:13,843
It's not that I can't compose. I won't.

427
00:34:14,343 --> 00:34:16,679
I'm done with such trivial things.

428
00:34:17,180 --> 00:34:20,308
But you were working just now.

429
00:34:20,892 --> 00:34:23,019
It was a beautiful piece.

430
00:34:24,395 --> 00:34:28,483
It's not for a film. That piece is for me.

431
00:34:29,066 --> 00:34:30,777
Only for me.

432
00:34:35,615 --> 00:34:38,201
- This is just like your name.
- Sir?

433
00:34:38,201 --> 00:34:40,661
Dull and tasteless.

434
00:34:40,661 --> 00:34:43,998
A beautiful piece? Don't make me laugh.

435
00:34:44,499 --> 00:34:49,086
A rubbish military weapon like you
has no right to talk about my art!

436
00:34:51,631 --> 00:34:53,090
My apologies, sir.

437
00:35:25,790 --> 00:35:27,542
How many did you kill?

438
00:35:28,126 --> 00:35:29,001
Sir?

439
00:35:29,001 --> 00:35:34,507
I'm asking how many people you killed
in the Central Asian War.

440
00:35:35,842 --> 00:35:40,304
The International Robot Laws
forbid me from harming humans.

441
00:35:40,805 --> 00:35:43,683
I see. So you killed your own kind.

442
00:35:45,101 --> 00:35:47,395
How many robots did you destroy?

443
00:35:49,147 --> 00:35:51,107
You lost count?

444
00:35:53,359 --> 00:35:54,527
Go away.

445
00:35:55,444 --> 00:35:58,823
A tasteless meal becomes
even blander with you around.

446
00:35:59,699 --> 00:36:01,033
I will take my leave, sir.

447
00:36:27,393 --> 00:36:30,938
What are you doing? Do not touch my piano!

448
00:36:32,523 --> 00:36:33,900
My apologies, sir.

449
00:36:35,610 --> 00:36:38,321
You compose with your piano only, I see.

450
00:36:38,946 --> 00:36:40,323
What about it?

451
00:36:40,948 --> 00:36:44,368
You have so much cutting-edge
musical equipment available to you.

452
00:36:45,953 --> 00:36:47,955
These are just like you.

453
00:36:48,623 --> 00:36:52,543
A fake violin, a fake trumpet,

454
00:36:52,543 --> 00:36:54,754
a fake orchestra.

455
00:36:54,754 --> 00:36:57,548
Pretend as they might,
they're nothing but machines.

456
00:36:59,592 --> 00:37:02,929
That's why I don't put in artificial eyes.

457
00:37:03,429 --> 00:37:08,100
Anything I could see
with the help of machines is fake.

458
00:37:08,100 --> 00:37:09,977
I have no need for it.

459
00:37:10,603 --> 00:37:14,440
{\an8}The real scenery is in my memories.

460
00:37:15,775 --> 00:37:17,902
The real scenery...

461
00:37:18,611 --> 00:37:22,073
The landscape of my hometown,
captured when I was able to see.

462
00:37:22,698 --> 00:37:25,534
When you were a child in Bohemia.

463
00:37:26,202 --> 00:37:28,246
Is that from the data too?

464
00:37:28,246 --> 00:37:32,250
There's nothing that truly matters
in such nonsense.

465
00:37:32,959 --> 00:37:34,877
The scenery of my hometown.

466
00:37:35,461 --> 00:37:37,672
{\an8}The green fields.

467
00:37:38,547 --> 00:37:40,341
{\an8}The gentle breeze.

468
00:37:40,341 --> 00:37:41,550
{\an8}And

469
00:37:42,385 --> 00:37:45,554
{\an8}that golden glow.

470
00:37:48,432 --> 00:37:51,394
<i>I will turn that scenery into music!</i>

471
00:39:07,636 --> 00:39:11,098
I told you not to touch my piano!

472
00:39:11,974 --> 00:39:13,726
My apologies, sir.

473
00:39:14,643 --> 00:39:18,147
If a machine like you
were to play from a score,

474
00:39:18,147 --> 00:39:20,024
any notes produced would be fake!

475
00:39:21,108 --> 00:39:21,942
Sir Duncan.

476
00:39:22,693 --> 00:39:24,403
Please pardon my imposition,

477
00:39:24,403 --> 00:39:28,282
but I heard you moaning
as you slept in your bedroom last night.

478
00:39:29,617 --> 00:39:33,704
But it also sounded like
you were humming, as well.

479
00:39:34,830 --> 00:39:38,709
And I believe that melody
would fit perfectly

480
00:39:39,293 --> 00:39:42,213
within the piece you are composing now.

481
00:39:42,797 --> 00:39:45,549
That section where you always stop midway...

482
00:39:47,259 --> 00:39:50,554
It's not precise, but it went like this.

483
00:39:53,224 --> 00:39:54,225
Get out!

484
00:39:54,725 --> 00:39:57,561
{\an8}I have no need for a robot like you.

485
00:39:58,062 --> 00:39:59,772
{\an8}Leave this residence!

486
00:39:59,772 --> 00:40:00,898
But...

487
00:40:01,398 --> 00:40:04,360
That's an order. Leave!

488
00:40:06,779 --> 00:40:07,655
Piano...

489
00:40:11,409 --> 00:40:14,120
I'd like to learn how to play piano.

490
00:40:15,371 --> 00:40:16,580
What did you say?

491
00:40:16,580 --> 00:40:22,545
As you say, no matter what I might play,
it may always be fake.

492
00:40:23,295 --> 00:40:27,049
But I'd like to get as close as possible
to the real thing.

493
00:40:27,049 --> 00:40:30,928
A weapon like you
could never play the piano!

494
00:40:40,438 --> 00:40:44,275
Stop it! That's nothing
for a tool of destruction to touch!

495
00:40:44,275 --> 00:40:47,069
{\an8}You belong on the battlefield!

496
00:40:48,654 --> 00:40:49,780
That is why.

497
00:40:52,408 --> 00:40:54,785
{\an8}That is why
I'd like to learn to play piano.

498
00:40:55,870 --> 00:40:59,707
Because I don't ever want to go
to a battlefield again.

499
00:41:03,878 --> 00:41:04,753
Mom!

500
00:41:06,422 --> 00:41:07,590
Mom!

501
00:41:09,633 --> 00:41:11,010
Mom!

502
00:41:12,094 --> 00:41:13,304
Mom!

503
00:41:19,518 --> 00:41:20,936
Wait, Mom!

504
00:41:25,274 --> 00:41:27,276
Mom, don't go!

505
00:41:27,276 --> 00:41:28,235
Mom!

506
00:41:30,070 --> 00:41:31,697
Mom!

507
00:41:33,449 --> 00:41:34,783
<i>Mom!</i>

508
00:41:40,331 --> 00:41:43,083
Are you there, North No.2?

509
00:41:45,794 --> 00:41:49,006
I told you not to come into my bedroom.

510
00:41:49,715 --> 00:41:53,802
Sir Duncan, your breakfast is ready.

511
00:41:57,348 --> 00:41:59,225
I thought I fired you.

512
00:42:02,061 --> 00:42:03,312
Are you still there?

513
00:42:13,239 --> 00:42:15,366
How many times do I have to tell you?

514
00:42:18,494 --> 00:42:20,871
Don't touch my piano!

515
00:42:21,539 --> 00:42:23,541
Sir Duncan, please listen.

516
00:42:24,166 --> 00:42:26,335
I think I've gotten a little better.

517
00:42:26,335 --> 00:42:28,712
"Gotten a little better"?

518
00:42:28,712 --> 00:42:32,591
The only improvement a machine can make
is to play with more precision!

519
00:42:34,218 --> 00:42:38,472
I will try and play the melody you hum
in your sleep, Sir Duncan.

520
00:42:54,572 --> 00:42:57,950
The sounds you produce are not music!

521
00:43:01,036 --> 00:43:02,621
These bloody things!

522
00:43:03,247 --> 00:43:08,502
"Just input the data,
and you can create infinite melodies?"

523
00:43:11,589 --> 00:43:15,217
That's not music at all!

524
00:43:16,135 --> 00:43:18,220
The machines will be ruined.

525
00:43:20,055 --> 00:43:22,182
Are you trying to protect your kind?

526
00:43:23,225 --> 00:43:27,438
Then let me ask you,
how many of your own kind did you destroy?

527
00:43:29,773 --> 00:43:34,653
Take off your cape and show the world
the hideous weapon that is your body!

528
00:43:34,653 --> 00:43:40,075
With that body of yours,
how many of your kind did you kill?

529
00:43:41,285 --> 00:43:45,205
Even a weapon of mass destruction
is programmed to behave obediently

530
00:43:45,205 --> 00:43:48,042
in front of its master, huh?

531
00:43:49,793 --> 00:43:51,378
Very well.

532
00:43:51,378 --> 00:43:56,258
I will give you
some genuine, accurate data about me.

533
00:43:56,800 --> 00:43:59,970
The reason I moan in my sleep...

534
00:44:00,596 --> 00:44:03,015
The nightmare I've been having
for so many years...

535
00:44:04,266 --> 00:44:07,019
No, not a nightmare.

536
00:44:07,019 --> 00:44:08,771
The reality of my past...

537
00:44:10,898 --> 00:44:15,736
<i>My real name is not Paul Duncan.
It's Paulo Holy.</i>

538
00:44:16,236 --> 00:44:19,114
<i>I was born in a poor household in Bohemia.</i>

539
00:44:19,907 --> 00:44:23,327
<i>My father died
before I was old enough to remember.</i>

540
00:44:23,869 --> 00:44:26,580
<i>I was struck
by a serious illness from birth,</i>

541
00:44:26,580 --> 00:44:32,670
<i>and my eyesight was poor,
so my only joy was singing songs.</i>

542
00:44:33,837 --> 00:44:36,090
<i>My mother was a beautiful woman.</i>

543
00:44:36,090 --> 00:44:40,886
<i>Even in tatters, she would turn the heads
of men when she walked down the street.</i>

544
00:44:41,679 --> 00:44:45,391
<i>That's why that parvenu approached her.</i>

545
00:44:46,642 --> 00:44:51,897
<i>And my mother became blinded
by her greed for that man's money.</i>

546
00:44:54,024 --> 00:44:57,486
She must have felt burdened by me.

547
00:44:58,112 --> 00:45:01,031
My mother left her sickly child.

548
00:45:02,324 --> 00:45:04,827
My mother abandoned me!

549
00:45:06,537 --> 00:45:10,916
<i>I was sent
to a boarding school in England.</i>

550
00:45:11,542 --> 00:45:13,085
<i>I had no friends,</i>

551
00:45:13,711 --> 00:45:17,464
<i>and my weak body
left me bullied year-round.</i>

552
00:45:18,132 --> 00:45:23,512
<i>But I was desperate
to continue my study of music.</i>

553
00:45:24,388 --> 00:45:26,473
<i>I must have strained myself continuously</i>

554
00:45:26,473 --> 00:45:29,435
<i>because, at one point,
I developed a persistent fever</i>,

555
00:45:29,435 --> 00:45:32,521
<i>and even my music studies
could not continue.</i>

556
00:45:40,821 --> 00:45:44,324
<i>I was sent around
from hospital to hospital,</i>

557
00:45:44,324 --> 00:45:46,702
<i>but my condition worsened.</i>

558
00:45:47,995 --> 00:45:52,374
<i>The doctors gave up on me,
and I never heard from my mother.</i>

559
00:45:54,585 --> 00:45:58,255
<i>I thought I was going to die.</i>

560
00:45:59,047 --> 00:46:03,927
<i>What a fitting last moment
for an abandoned child.</i>

561
00:46:05,971 --> 00:46:08,849
<i>That's when a Japanese doctor appeared.</i>

562
00:46:09,433 --> 00:46:13,437
<i>Technically, he wasn't a doctor
because he was unlicensed.</i>

563
00:46:14,980 --> 00:46:17,274
I will save your life.

564
00:46:18,442 --> 00:46:22,362
But you might go blind as a result.

565
00:46:26,158 --> 00:46:28,494
<i>The surgery was a success.</i>

566
00:46:29,328 --> 00:46:33,290
<i>But just as the unlicensed doctor said,</i>

567
00:46:33,290 --> 00:46:36,210
<i>my eyesight deteriorated day by day.</i>

568
00:46:36,919 --> 00:46:38,670
<i>With the little time I had left,</i>

569
00:46:39,254 --> 00:46:43,675
<i>I threw myself even more
into the study of music.</i>

570
00:46:44,676 --> 00:46:46,845
<i>Music was all I had.</i>

571
00:46:48,138 --> 00:46:50,015
<i>More music!</i>

572
00:46:50,641 --> 00:46:52,726
<i>More!</i>

573
00:46:53,519 --> 00:46:54,937
<i>More!</i>

574
00:46:58,315 --> 00:46:59,358
<i>And finally,</i>

575
00:47:00,442 --> 00:47:01,944
<i>the darkness came.</i>

576
00:47:04,571 --> 00:47:07,574
A few years later,
I was informed of my mother's death.

577
00:47:08,367 --> 00:47:12,371
She never was able to marry that parvenu.

578
00:47:12,371 --> 00:47:15,374
I heard she died all alone.

579
00:47:15,916 --> 00:47:18,043
Serves her right for abandoning her child.

580
00:47:18,877 --> 00:47:24,091
But you know what?
This castle belonged to that parvenu.

581
00:47:24,633 --> 00:47:27,928
From Paulo Holy to the genius Paul Duncan.

582
00:47:28,846 --> 00:47:32,975
I became a maestro of the music world
and made the castle mine.

583
00:47:34,101 --> 00:47:35,269
Mother!

584
00:47:35,269 --> 00:47:38,272
This is what you wanted.

585
00:47:39,147 --> 00:47:43,277
This is what you sought
at the cost of abandoning your child!

586
00:47:44,528 --> 00:47:49,908
Now, Mother, I will show you
what is truly important.

587
00:47:50,409 --> 00:47:53,203
The landscape of our hometown
that you deserted!

588
00:47:53,203 --> 00:47:57,666
<i>I will turn
that magnificent scenery into music!</i>

589
00:47:57,666 --> 00:48:03,171
{\an8}I will show you what it is
that humans should never throw away!

590
00:48:07,551 --> 00:48:08,510
Sir Duncan.

591
00:48:09,136 --> 00:48:10,762
Your mother--

592
00:48:10,762 --> 00:48:11,889
Silence!

593
00:48:14,933 --> 00:48:18,353
I'll write you a letter of recommendation.
Leave this place tomorrow.

594
00:48:50,010 --> 00:48:52,387
<i>That is why
I'd like to learn to play piano.</i>

595
00:48:53,847 --> 00:48:57,225
<i>Because I don't ever want to go
to a battlefield again.</i>

596
00:49:58,495 --> 00:50:01,081
I guess he improved a little.

597
00:50:25,647 --> 00:50:29,735
Charging himself in preparation
for tomorrow's departure?

598
00:50:30,235 --> 00:50:31,695
Damn machine.

599
00:50:45,542 --> 00:50:47,502
Is he having a nightmare?

600
00:50:53,967 --> 00:50:57,804
Robots have dreams too?

601
00:51:26,333 --> 00:51:30,504
"It's not that I can't compose.
I won't," huh?

602
00:51:33,548 --> 00:51:34,382
Hey.

603
00:51:36,301 --> 00:51:37,552
North No.2.

604
00:51:39,179 --> 00:51:41,098
North No.2! Hey!

605
00:51:44,810 --> 00:51:46,853
He really left, huh?

606
00:51:52,901 --> 00:51:55,529
Maybe I really can't compose anymore.

607
00:52:12,379 --> 00:52:14,673
How long are you going to make me wait?

608
00:52:14,673 --> 00:52:17,050
When is the replacement butler coming--

609
00:52:17,050 --> 00:52:19,761
<i>Hello, my name is Marshall
from MCM Pictures.</i>

610
00:52:20,470 --> 00:52:22,264
Oh, you're just a movie guy.

611
00:52:22,973 --> 00:52:25,433
<i>Is something wrong, Sir Duncan?</i>

612
00:52:25,934 --> 00:52:29,980
No, I just fired
a butler robot the other day.

613
00:52:30,730 --> 00:52:32,107
So, what do you want?

614
00:52:32,607 --> 00:52:36,611
<i>Well, I'm actually calling
about a score for a certain film.</i>

615
00:52:37,654 --> 00:52:39,197
A job offer, huh?

616
00:52:39,698 --> 00:52:42,784
Tell me the details.
I might be interested.

617
00:52:43,368 --> 00:52:45,078
<i>Thank you, sir.</i>

618
00:52:45,078 --> 00:52:49,833
<i>I was wondering if you would consent
to the reuse of one of your old scores.</i>

619
00:52:49,833 --> 00:52:52,377
What? You're not asking for a new piece?

620
00:52:52,377 --> 00:52:57,549
<i>Oh! It was my understanding
that you had retired, Sir Duncan.</i>

621
00:53:00,594 --> 00:53:02,596
Use it however you want.

622
00:53:02,596 --> 00:53:04,222
<i>Oh, Sir Duncan--</i>

623
00:53:06,975 --> 00:53:08,602
<i>There is a new message.</i>

624
00:53:13,106 --> 00:53:17,027
<i>This is Russell from the Planning Office
at the British Philharmonic Orchestra.</i>

625
00:53:17,652 --> 00:53:21,948
<i>Regarding the performance of your suite
we discussed before,</i>

626
00:53:22,616 --> 00:53:26,328
<i>unfortunately, we have decided
to cancel it due to various circumstances.</i>

627
00:53:26,328 --> 00:53:30,081
<i>We are very sorry about this.
If another opportunity arises, we will...</i>

628
00:53:51,561 --> 00:53:52,938
<i>I heard you moaning,</i>

629
00:53:54,022 --> 00:53:58,109
<i>and I believe that melody
would fit perfectly...</i>

630
00:55:46,509 --> 00:55:47,719
Sir Duncan.

631
00:55:49,429 --> 00:55:51,306
I have returned.

632
00:55:53,183 --> 00:55:56,269
What now? I thought I told you to leave.

633
00:55:56,936 --> 00:55:58,855
I went to Bohemia.

634
00:55:59,355 --> 00:56:01,191
To your hometown, Sir Duncan.

635
00:56:02,192 --> 00:56:04,319
What business did you have there?

636
00:56:04,819 --> 00:56:07,238
I went to collect songs.

637
00:56:08,531 --> 00:56:11,659
In the process of collecting
many folk songs from that region,

638
00:56:12,911 --> 00:56:13,995
I have found it,

639
00:56:14,496 --> 00:56:18,583
the melody you hum in your sleep.

640
00:56:20,627 --> 00:56:22,212
I will sing it now.

641
00:56:22,212 --> 00:56:25,882
Stop! I don't want to hear a machine sing!

642
00:56:26,382 --> 00:56:29,469
Don't intrude on my nightmare any further!

643
00:56:29,469 --> 00:56:33,264
Humans have things we would rather forget!

644
00:56:34,766 --> 00:56:37,602
Sir Duncan, your dream is not a nightmare.

645
00:56:40,313 --> 00:56:44,150
It's not something that should be erased
like my dreams.

646
00:56:46,111 --> 00:56:49,614
Just as you said,
I am nothing but a weapon.

647
00:56:50,365 --> 00:56:55,954
In the 39th Central Asian War,
I neutralized many enemy robots...

648
00:56:56,830 --> 00:57:02,418
No, I destroyed tens of thousands
of my own kind.

649
00:57:03,253 --> 00:57:04,462
Those memories,

650
00:57:05,046 --> 00:57:07,882
the memories of killing
countless of my kind,

651
00:57:08,508 --> 00:57:11,636
my artificial intelligence plays them
again and again in my mind.

652
00:57:13,596 --> 00:57:16,808
I met a certain old man in Bohemia.

653
00:57:18,101 --> 00:57:20,353
He was very knowledgeable
about folk songs,

654
00:57:20,937 --> 00:57:23,022
and he knew that particular song as well.

655
00:57:24,190 --> 00:57:30,321
He also remembered that there was
a wonderful singer of that song.

656
00:57:32,198 --> 00:57:33,992
Your mother.

657
00:57:36,411 --> 00:57:39,122
The data I have in my mind
about you, Sir Duncan,

658
00:57:39,622 --> 00:57:42,458
includes that of your mother.

659
00:57:43,418 --> 00:57:49,507
Your mother did not abandon you
when you were suffering from illness.

660
00:57:49,507 --> 00:57:56,556
She approached a multimillionaire,
Jonathan Thorn, to attain treatment.

661
00:57:57,807 --> 00:58:04,314
That's how she afforded the astronomical
fee for the doctor who saved your life.

662
00:58:06,649 --> 00:58:08,985
You were never abandoned.

663
00:58:09,694 --> 00:58:15,408
Your mother was right by your side
when you went blind.

664
00:58:16,451 --> 00:58:23,249
{\an8}But learning your hatred toward her,
she couldn't extend her hand.

665
00:58:24,584 --> 00:58:26,085
No.

666
00:58:28,004 --> 00:58:29,172
That can't be.

667
00:58:29,881 --> 00:58:30,715
It's true.

668
00:58:31,633 --> 00:58:33,718
When you remember your hometown,

669
00:58:34,219 --> 00:58:37,013
are you not excluding
a very important memory?

670
00:58:39,641 --> 00:58:41,684
The old man in the village told me

671
00:58:42,602 --> 00:58:45,855
how you and your mother held hands
and sang this song together

672
00:58:46,689 --> 00:58:51,986
as you watched the sun setting
into the fields of your homeland.

673
00:59:32,944 --> 00:59:33,778
<i>Mom...</i>

674
00:59:40,743 --> 00:59:41,953
Mom...

675
00:59:45,957 --> 00:59:47,292
I apologize.

676
00:59:48,126 --> 00:59:49,752
It's only the song of a machine.

677
00:59:52,380 --> 00:59:55,216
Your dream is not a nightmare.

678
00:59:56,759 --> 00:59:58,720
Your dream is not like mine.

679
01:00:03,016 --> 01:00:04,767
North No.2...

680
01:00:06,769 --> 01:00:10,607
{\an8}don't ever go back to the battlefield.

681
01:00:16,654 --> 01:00:19,073
Let's practice the piano.

682
01:00:22,243 --> 01:00:23,202
Yes, sir.

683
01:02:25,241 --> 01:02:26,492
North No.2!

684
01:02:27,118 --> 01:02:29,287
Hey, North No.2!

685
01:02:29,871 --> 01:02:31,622
Yes, Sir Duncan?

686
01:02:32,290 --> 01:02:34,917
It's finally finished. Give it a listen.

687
01:02:35,626 --> 01:02:39,005
Yes, sir. I would love to listen to it.

688
01:02:39,589 --> 01:02:40,757
However, just now...

689
01:02:40,757 --> 01:02:42,341
Huh? What's the matter?

690
01:02:43,176 --> 01:02:46,304
Something is approaching this direction.

691
01:02:46,304 --> 01:02:47,680
"Something"?

692
01:02:48,181 --> 01:02:51,517
Is it a friend visiting you, perhaps?

693
01:02:52,143 --> 01:02:56,481
Did you hear the news from Switzerland
a few days ago, sir?

694
01:02:57,064 --> 01:02:58,900
The news from Switzerland?

695
01:02:58,900 --> 01:03:05,448
Oh, about the robot called Mont Blanc
getting destroyed in a tornado?

696
01:03:06,491 --> 01:03:11,162
A tornado occurred about 100 km from here
just a moment ago.

697
01:03:17,919 --> 01:03:20,713
Some sort of threat is approaching.

698
01:03:23,257 --> 01:03:24,592
Hey!

699
01:03:26,344 --> 01:03:27,762
I shall return soon.

700
01:03:28,763 --> 01:03:30,473
North No.2!

701
01:04:02,421 --> 01:04:03,965
North No.2.

702
01:04:06,008 --> 01:04:07,301
North No.2!

703
01:04:11,806 --> 01:04:13,015
North...

704
01:04:20,481 --> 01:04:23,359
What in the world...

705
01:04:29,365 --> 01:04:31,784
What is happening?

706
01:04:39,250 --> 01:04:40,293
North No.2...

707
01:04:52,430 --> 01:04:53,806
This is...

708
01:05:01,397 --> 01:05:02,732
that song.

709
01:05:04,191 --> 01:05:06,611
The song is spreading

710
01:05:07,653 --> 01:05:09,030
across the entire sky.

711
01:05:15,536 --> 01:05:17,455
North No.2.

712
01:05:22,627 --> 01:05:25,922
North No.2 is singing.

713
01:05:36,891 --> 01:05:41,228
Stop singing out here and come home soon.

714
01:05:42,897 --> 01:05:44,231
North No.2,

715
01:05:46,400 --> 01:05:49,403
it's time for our piano practice.

716
01:06:14,804 --> 01:06:16,639
- It's really awesome!
- Really?

717
01:06:36,450 --> 01:06:37,743
Is that a snail?

718
01:06:38,494 --> 01:06:39,412
Yes.

719
01:06:44,041 --> 01:06:45,626
Nice to meet you.

720
01:06:47,628 --> 01:06:49,922
You must be Atom.

721
01:06:52,675 --> 01:06:53,551
Yes.

722
01:09:23,159 --> 01:09:26,912
{\an8}Subtitle translation by: Astrid Oliver

